				\begin{document}$$\theta_{1} = \theta$$\end{document}

On the other side, by extending the incident beam we see that the angle θ2 is divided into two angles, one equal to θ1 (and thus θ) and the other one equal to α which is again clear from the figure. This yields the following relation:3θ2=θ+α\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\theta_{2} = \theta + \alpha$$\end{document}

Using Eqs. (2) and (3), Eq. (1) can be rewritten in the following way:4n1sinθ=n0sin(θ+α)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$n_{1} \sin \theta = n_{0} \sin (\theta + \alpha )$$\end{document}

Thus n0 in this equation is the refractive index of the air and can be set equal to 1. Parameter n1 is the refractive index of the medium where for Plexiglas is around 1.49. The only remaining parameter to be determined for the Eq. (4) to yield the value of the groove’s angle θ, is α. This angle could be simply calculated from simple trigonometric relations. The sine of this angle is the ratio of the groove distance from the center of the lens and its distance from the focal line:5sinα=(N-1+N/2)Δ(N-1+N/2)Δ2+f2⇒α=sin-1(N-1+N/2)Δ(N-1+N/2)Δ2+f2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \sin \alpha = \frac{(N - 1 + N/2)\Delta }{{\sqrt {\left( {(N - 1 + N/2)\Delta } \right)^{2} + f^{2} } }}\begin{array}{*{20}c} {} & {} \\ \end{array} \Rightarrow \hfill \\ \alpha = \sin^{ - 1} \left( {\frac{(N - 1 + N/2)\Delta }{{\sqrt {\left( {(N - 1 + N/2)\Delta } \right)^{2} + f^{2} } }}} \right) \hfill \\ \end{aligned}$$\end{document}where Δ is the width of each groove and N is the number of grooves counting from the center part. By determining α from Eq. (4), the groove’s angle θ could be extracted using Eq. (4).
